Cybersecurity Threats Analysis (2015-2024)

This project analyzes global cybersecurity threats data from 2015 to 2024, examining attack patterns, financial impacts, and defense mechanisms across countries and industries.

In[2]:
# Create a cursor object to interact with the database
cursor = connection.cursor()

# SQL query to retrieve data from a table
query = "SELECT * FROM global_cybersecurity_threats"  
cursor.execute(query)

# Fetch all results into a pandas DataFrame
columns = [desc[0] for desc in cursor.description]  # Get column names
data = cursor.fetchall()

Key Questions and Answers

Q1: Which country experienced the highest number of cyber attacks between 2015-2024?

In[28]:
top_country = df['Country'].value_counts().idxmax()
top_country_count = df['Country'].value_counts().max()
print(f"A1: {top_country} experienced the highest number of cyber attacks with {top_country_count} incidents.")

A1: UK experienced the highest number of cyber attacks with 321 incidents.

Q2: What is the most common type of cyber attack?

In[29]:
common_attack = df['Attack Type'].value_counts().idxmax()
common_attack_count = df['Attack Type'].value_counts().max()
print(f"A2: The most common attack type is {common_attack} with {common_attack_count} incidents.")

A2: The most common attack type is DDoS with 531 incidents.

Q3: Which industry suffered the highest financial losses due to cyber attacks?

In[30]:
industry_max_loss = df.groupby('Target Industry')['Financial Loss (in Million $)'].sum().idxmax()
max_loss = df.groupby('Target Industry')['Financial Loss (in Million $)'].sum().max()
print(f"A3: The {industry_max_loss} industry suffered the highest financial losses totaling ${max_loss:.2f} million.")

A3: The IT industry suffered the highest financial losses totaling $24805.00 million.

Q4: What is the most exploited security vulnerability?

In[31]:
common_vuln = df['Security Vulnerability Type'].value_counts().idxmax()
common_vuln_count = df['Security Vulnerability Type'].value_counts().max()
print(f"A4: The most exploited vulnerability is '{common_vuln}' with {common_vuln_count} incidents.")

A4: The most exploited vulnerability is 'Zero-day' with 785 incidents.

Q5: Which attack type takes the longest to resolve on average?

In[32]:
longest_resolution = df.groupby('Attack Type')['Incident Resolution Time (in Hours)'].mean().idxmax()
avg_time = df.groupby('Attack Type')['Incident Resolution Time (in Hours)'].mean().max()
print(f" {longest_resolution} attacks take the longest to resolve with an average of {avg_time:.1f} hours.")

 Malware attacks take the longest to resolve with an average of 37.1 hours.

Q6: Has the average resolution time for incidents improved over the years?

In[33]:
resolution_trend = df.groupby('Year')['Incident Resolution Time (in Hours)'].mean()
if resolution_trend.iloc[-1] < resolution_trend.iloc[0]:
    trend = "improved"
else:
    trend = "not improved" if resolution_trend.iloc[-1] == resolution_trend.iloc[0] else "worsened"
print(f"A6: The average resolution time has {trend} from {resolution_trend.iloc[0]:.1f} hours in {resolution_trend.index[0]} to {resolution_trend.iloc[-1]:.1f} hours in {resolution_trend.index[-1]}.")

A6: The average resolution time has improved from 38.4 hours in 2015 to 35.9 hours in 2024.

Q7: What is the most common defense mechanism used against cyber attacks?

In[34]:
common_defense = df['Defense Mechanism Used'].value_counts().idxmax()
common_defense_count = df['Defense Mechanism Used'].value_counts().max()
print(f" The most common defense mechanism used is {common_defense} with {common_defense_count} incidents.")

 The most common defense mechanism used is Antivirus with 628 incidents.

Q8: Which attack source is most responsible for cyber attacks?

In[35]:
common_source = df['Attack Source'].value_counts().idxmax()
common_source_count = df['Attack Source'].value_counts().max()
print(f"The most common attack source is {common_source} responsible for {common_source_count} incidents.")

The most common attack source is Nation-state responsible for 794 incidents.

Q9: Is there a correlation between financial loss and number of affected users?

In[36]:
correlation = df['Financial Loss (in Million $)'].corr(df['Number of Affected Users'])
print(f" The correlation between financial loss and number of affected users is {correlation:.2f}, indicating a {'positive' if correlation > 0 else 'negative' if correlation < 0 else 'no'} relationship.")

 The correlation between financial loss and number of affected users is 0.00, indicating a positive relationship.

Q10: How has the distribution of attack types changed over the years?

In[37]:
# Get top 5 attack types
top_attacks = df['Attack Type'].value_counts().head(5).index

# Filter data for top attacks
df_top_attacks = df[df['Attack Type'].isin(top_attacks)]

# Plot
plt.figure(figsize=(14, 8))
sns.countplot(x='Year', hue='Attack Type', data=df_top_attacks, hue_order=top_attacks)
plt.title('Trend of Top 5 Attack Types Over Years', fontsize=16)
plt.xlabel('Year', fontsize=14)
plt.ylabel('Count', fontsize=14)
plt.legend(title='Attack Type', bbox_to_anchor=(1.05, 1), loc='upper left')
plt.xticks(rotation=45)
plt.show()

print(" The visualization above shows how the distribution of top 5 attack types has changed over the years.")

 The visualization above shows how the distribution of top 5 attack types has changed over the years.

Conclusion

This analysis provides comprehensive insights into global cybersecurity threats from 2015 to 2024. Key findings include:

The most targeted countries and industries

The most common attack types and their financial impacts

Trends in vulnerabilities and defense mechanisms

Changes in incident resolution times

Relationships between different variables

The visualizations help identify patterns and trends that can inform cybersecurity strategies and resource allocation for different industries and regions.

In[38]:
import nbformat
from nbconvert import HTMLExporter

# Load the Jupyter notebook (.ipynb) file
with open('Cybersecurity_Threats_Analysis.ipynb', 'r') as f:
    notebook_content = nbformat.read(f, as_version=4)

# Initialize the HTMLExporter
html_exporter = HTMLExporter()

# Convert the notebook to HTML format
html_data, resources = html_exporter.from_notebook_node(notebook_content)

# Save the HTML output to a new HTML file
with open('Cybersecurity_Threats_Analysis.html', 'w') as f:
    f.write(html_data)

print("Notebook has been converted to HTML and saved as output_notebook.html.")

Notebook has been converted to HTML and saved as output_notebook.html.
